<font color="#FF0000">THE WAY OF THE WORLD</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 11 15:06:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Terry,<br>
     In many ways, things haven't changed, just the outward form.  About the time of the war, what eventually became a mass migration of jobs from city to suburb and rustbelt to sunbelt got underway.  Companies weren't downsizing per se, but they began shifting jobs from place to place with ever increasing frequency for lower labor costs, lower taxes, more space, newer facilities.  Obligations to shareholders might be acknowledged, but obligations to employees, who put blood and sweat into building the company?  Any acknowledgement of these gets mostly gets honored in the breach.  Philadelphia, where I now live hemoraged over a million jobs since 1965, and before the word &quot;downsizing&quot; entered the vocabulary.  Stetson hats, Baldwin locomotives, Breyer's ice cream... the list goes on and on.<br>
     To survive and prosper, business needs moral employees and a stable civic environment.  But too few business owners  pay more than lip service to their responsibilities for any breakdown in society.  That might require real sacrifice, and to sacrifice short term profit for long term wellbeing, seems to be beyond whatever moral compass guides most CEOs and their shareholders.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


